const a = [
  {"id":12664,"text":"Which of the following structures passes through the diaphragm with the esophagus?","explanation":"The structure that passes through the diaphragm with the esophagus is the **Right vagus nerve**.\r\n\r\nThe diaphragm has three major openings: the caval opening (for the inferior vena cava), the esophageal hiatus (for the esophagus and the vagal trunks), and the aortic hiatus (for the aorta, thoracic duct, and azygos vein). The esophageal hiatus is situated in the right crus of the diaphragm at the level of the T10 vertebra. The right vagus nerve (posterior vagal trunk) and the left vagus nerve (anterior vagal trunk) pass through this hiatus alongside the esophagus. The right vagus nerve typically gives off branches around the esophagus and contributes to the formation of the esophageal plexus.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 536.","responses":[{"text":"Phrenic nerves","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Right vagus nerve","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Sympathetic trunk","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thoracic duct","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Azygos vein","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21036,"text":"A patient underwent a chest CT scan that revealed a mass in the anterior mediastinum. Among the following conditions, what is the most likely cause of the mass?","explanation":null,"reference":"Drake, Richard L. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed., Elsevier, 2020:185","responses":[{"text":"Diaphragmatic hernia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thymoma","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Esophageal tear","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fibroma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Carcinoma of bronchi","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21037,"text":"A 4-year-old boy was brought to the emergency department. The mother tells that the boy has swallowed a small bead while playing. Which of the following is the most appropriate reason for this bead to enter the right lung?","explanation":null,"reference":"Moore, Keith L., et al. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed., Wolters Kluwer, 2018: 343","responses":[{"text":"Right lung has one lobe more than left lung","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Right lung is heavier than the left lung","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Right bronchus is more vertically placed than the left one","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Right lung is shorter than the left lung","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Right bronchus is narrower than the left one","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21038,"text":"While discussing important clinical landmarks, students consider the significant ones in\r\nrelation to the division of mediastinum. Which of the following is primarily considered a landmark to divide the mediastinum?","explanation":null,"reference":"Moore, Keith L., et al. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed., Wolters Kluwer, 2018: 297","responses":[{"text":"Foramen of Winslow","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Angle of louis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Thoracic inlet","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"12th thoracic vertebra","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Costodiaphragmatic recess","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21039,"text":"A 60-year-old patient has a profuse amount of fluid in the left pleural cavity due to \r\nacute pleurisy. Where would the fluid accumulate?","explanation":null,"reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 329.","responses":[{"text":"Lingula","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Costodiaphragmatic recess","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hilar reflection","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Costomediastinal recess","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cupola","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21041,"text":"Which of the following branches of typical intercostal nerves arise near the angle of ribs?","explanation":null,"reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 310.","responses":[{"text":"Anterior cutaneous","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Muscular branch","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rami communicantes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Collateral","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Lateral cutaneous","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21042,"text":"Which of the following is an incorrect statement regarding posterior intercostal arteries?","explanation":null,"reference":"Moore, Keith L., et al. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed., Wolters Kluwer, 2018: 314","responses":[{"text":"Eleven in number on each side","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Content of costal groove","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Give mammary branches to the breast","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Give right bronchial artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"All are branches of descending thoracic aorta","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":21043,"text":"Which of the following joints of the thorax is a primary cartilaginous joint?","explanation":null,"reference":"Moore, Keith L., et al. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed., Wolters Kluwer, 2018: 299. Table 4.1","responses":[{"text":"Second sternocostal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fourth sternocostal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Manubriosternal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fifth sternocostal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"First sternocostal","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":21044,"text":"Which of the following pairs of ribs is classified as vertebrochondral ribs?","explanation":null,"reference":"Moore, Keith L., et al. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed., Wolters Kluwer, 2018: 292.","responses":[{"text":"10 and 11","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"2 till 7","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"1 till 7","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"8, 9 and 10","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"11 and 12","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21046,"text":"A patient comes to the chest clinic with the complaint of chest pain felt in the ribs. After examination, a diagnosis of pressure on intercostal nerves was made. This compression on intercostal nerves was leading to spasms of the muscles being innervated by these nerves. Which of the following muscles would be unaffected in this scenario?","explanation":null,"reference":"Drake, Richard L. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed., Elsevier, 2020: 143. Table 3.1.","responses":[{"text":"Innermost intercostal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Internal intercostal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pectoralis major","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Subcostal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"External intercostal","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21080,"text":"In which of the  following weeks do the terminal bronchioles become larger to form two or more respiratory bronchioles\r\nand primordial alveolar ducts are formed?","explanation":null,"reference":"(1) Sadler TW. Langman’s Medical Embryology. 14th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 228. Table 14.1.\r\n\r\n(2) Moore, Keith L., et al. The Developing Human: Clinically Oriented Embryology. 11th ed., Saunders/Elsevier, 2020: 201.","responses":[{"text":"28 to 32","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"11 to 16 weeks","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"5 to 10 weeks","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"33 to 40","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"16 to 25 weeks","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":21081,"text":"Which of the following structures does not participate in forming the thoracoabdominal diaphragm?","explanation":null,"reference":"Moore, Keith L., et al. The Developing Human: Clinically Oriented Embryology. 11th ed., Saunders/Elsevier, 2020: 146.","responses":[{"text":"Mesentry of oesophagus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Myoblast from cervical somites","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pleuropericardial folds","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Septum transversum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pleuroperitoneal membrane","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21082,"text":"The trachea is the part of the conducting portion of the respiratory system. The mucosa is lined by pseudostratified ciliated columnar epithelium. Glands in the submucosa cartilage and adventitia. Which of the following structures has the same\r\nhistological appearance as the trachea?","explanation":null,"reference":"Mescher, Anthony L. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 15th ed., McGraw-Hill Medical, 2018: 356","responses":[{"text":"Respiratory bronchioles","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Terminal bronchioles","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intrapulmonary bronchus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pre-terminal bronchioles","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Extrapulmonary bronchus","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":21083,"text":"During chest auscultation, a physician instructs his patient to inhale deeply. Which of the following muscles are accountable for facilitating this ventilation procedure?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall, John E., and Michael E. Hall. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed., Elsevier, 2020: 491","responses":[{"text":"Scalenes and internal intercostals","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Diaphragm and internal intercostal muscles","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Diaphragm and external intercostal muscles","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Rectus abdominus and internal intercostals","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Internal and external intercostal muscles","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21084,"text":"A 50-year-old smoker is diagnosed with restrictive lung disease, which affects his\r\nlung tissue's ability to expand. Which of the following is most likely to be reduced in this condition?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall, John E., and Michael E. Hall. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed., Elsevier, 2020: 542","responses":[{"text":"Tidal volume","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inspiratory reserve volume","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vital capacity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Expiratory reserve volume","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Residual volume","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":21085,"text":"A person is hiking at a high altitude mountain, where the air has a lower oxygen concentration. As a result, they experience changes in their respiratory rate and depth to adapt to the lower oxygen levels. Which of the following physiological mechanisms primarily regulates respiration in this situation?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall, John E., and Michael E. Hall. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed., Elsevier, 2020: 536","responses":[{"text":"The somatic nervous system","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Central chemoreceptors in the medulla oblongata","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"The stretch receptors in the lungs","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Peripheral chemoreceptors in the carotid bodies","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The Hering-Breuer reflex","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21087,"text":"Which of the following effects on the respiratory system occurs due to parasympathetic stimulation?","explanation":null,"reference":"Katzung BG, Todd W. Vanderah. Basic and Clinical Pharmacology. 15th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2021: 101. Table 6-3.","responses":[{"text":"Bronchoconstriction via nicotinic receptors","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bronchoconstriction via alpha 1 receptors","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bronchoconstriction via muscarinic receptors","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Bronchodilation due to acetylcholine receptor activation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bronchodilation via beta 2 receptors","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21088,"text":"In a healthy individual which one of the following is the primary regulating variable of central chemoreceptors?","explanation":null,"reference":"(1) Hall, John E., and Michael E. Hall. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed., Elsevier, 2020: 533.\r\n\r\n(2) Costanzo L. Costanzo Physiology. 7th ed. Elsevier, Inc; 2021: 233-234.","responses":[{"text":"Arterial pH","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Input from irritant receptors","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"PaO2","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Input from stretch receptors","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"PaCO2","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":21149,"text":"An 80-year-old obese person has been diagnosed with sleep apnea, a condition\r\nwhere he experiences repeated pauses in breathing during sleep. This is primarily\r\ndue to which of the following?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall, John E., and Michael E. Hall. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed., Elsevier, 2020: 539.","responses":[{"text":"Overactive diaphragm muscles","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"An increase in blood oxygen levels","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"A decrease in lung compliance","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Relaxation of pharyngeal muscles","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"A decrease in carbon dioxide levels","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21150,"text":"Repaying the oxygen debt after exercise is primarily achieved to regulate which of the following processes?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall, John E., and Michael E. Hall. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed., Elsevier, 2020: 895.","responses":[{"text":"Elevate body temperature","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Oxygen bound with myoglobin only","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Reconvert phosphocreatine to creatinine and phosphate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Reconvert ATP and ADP to AMP","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Reconvert the lactic acid back into glucose","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":21151,"text":"A 20-year-old patient with asthma is prescribed an inhaler that contains a bronchodilator. Which receptors are inhibited by the bronchodilator to help alleviate her asthma symptoms?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall, John E., and Michael E. Hall. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed., Elsevier, 2020: 775","responses":[{"text":"Beta-1 adrenergic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Beta-3 adrenergic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Beta-2 adrenergic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nicotinic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Muscarinic","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":21152,"text":"Following a road traffic accident, a 25-year-old young man experiences breathing difficulties. Upon arrival at the emergency department, a lung function test was conducted, revealing a reduction in his functional residual capacity. What does this reduced capacity signify?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall, John E., and Michael E. Hall. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed., Elsevier, 2020: 495.","responses":[{"text":"The volume of air that lingers in the lung after a normal exhalation","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"The volume of air expelled after a standard exhalation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The sum of inspiratory reserve volume and tidal volume","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The volume of air inhaled and exhaled during a typical breath","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The volume of air that stays in the lung after a complete exhalation","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21153,"text":"A 20-year-old male presents to the emergency department with a fractured rib. The patient experiences painful breathing and thus takes rapid, shallow breaths. His respiratory rate is 40 breaths per minute with a tidal volume of 200 ml. What would be his alveolar ventilation rate?","explanation":null,"reference":"Costanzo L. Costanzo Physiology. 7th ed. Elsevier, Inc; 2021: 194.","responses":[{"text":"6000 ml/min","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"2000 ml/min","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"400 ml/min","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"200 ml/min","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"4600 ml/min","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21154,"text":"A patient with a history of chronic lung disease is experiencing decreased lung compliance. What is the primary factor contributing to this reduction in lung compliance?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall, John E., and Michael E. Hall. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed., Elsevier, 2020: 493.","responses":[{"text":"Reduced alveolar surface area","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Decreased thoracic cage flexibility","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased elastic recoil of the lungs","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Decreased surfactant production","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Elevated intrapleural pressure","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21155,"text":"In which of the following conditions is cyanosis absent?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall, John E., and Michael E. Hall. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed., Elsevier, 2020: 547-548.","responses":[{"text":"High altitude pulmonary edema","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Impaired gas exchange secondary to pneumonia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pulmonary embolism leading to V/Q mismatch","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Right to left shunt in congenital heart disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aplastic anemia with 4g/dl Hb","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":21156,"text":"A 45-year-old male received a penetrating stab wound on the chest wall resulting in intrapleural pressure becoming equal to atmospheric pressure. This change in the pressure would cause which one of the following effects on the lung?","explanation":null,"reference":"Costanzo, Linda. Costanzo Physiology. 7th ed., Elsevier, Inc, 2021: 200.","responses":[{"text":"Reduced work of breathing","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Decreased airway resistance","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased surfactant","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased compliance","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Collapse of alveoli","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":21158,"text":"A 70-year-old male who has smoked 50 cigarettes per day for 45 years complains of shortness of breath and is diagnosed with chronic emphysema. Which of the following changes are present in this patient with respect to lung compliance, lung elastic recoil, and total lung capacity as compared to a healthy non-smoker?","explanation":null,"reference":"(1) Costanzo L. Costanzo Physiology. 7th ed. Elsevier, Inc; 2021: 202.\r\n\r\n(2) Hall, John E., and Michael E. Hall. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed., Elsevier, 2020: 543-544.","responses":[{"text":"Decreased, decreased, decreased","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Decreased, decreased, increased","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased, decreased, increased","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased, decreased, decreased","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Decreased, increased, increased","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21167,"text":"A 60-year-old male suffered a stroke that resulted in damage to an area that controls forced expiration during rest and exercise. Which one of the following was most likely affected in this individual?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall, John E., and Michael E. Hall. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed., Elsevier, 2020: 532","responses":[{"text":"Pneumotaxic center","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ventral respiratory group","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pre-Botzinger complex","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dorsal respiratory group","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Apneustic center","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21168,"text":"A healthy 25-year-old woman reports coughing paroxysms when the temperature goes below freezing. Which of the following sensory receptors may have triggered this response?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 538.","responses":[{"text":"Pulmonary stretch receptors","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Central chemoreceptors","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Juxtapulmonary capillary receptors","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Peripheral chemoreceptors","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Irritant receptors","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":21169,"text":"During strenuous exercise, an athlete's alveolar ventilation increases to 6 L per minute while pulmonary blood flow rises to 7.5 L per minute. Which one of the following V/Q ratios is present at this moment?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall, John E., and Michael E. Hall. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed., Elsevier, 2020: 518.","responses":[{"text":"1.2","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"0.5","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"0.6","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"0.8","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"0.7","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21170,"text":"Which one of the following factors keeps the pulmonary alveoli dry under normal conditions?","explanation":"The pulmonary alveoli remain dry under normal conditions due to the **low vapor pressure of water in inspired air**. This is essential to prevent fluid accumulation within the alveoli, which could impair gas exchange. The inspired air, as it travels through the respiratory passages, is warmed and humidified, but the water vapor pressure remains low to avoid excessive moisture within the alveoli.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nThe phagocytic activity of alveolar macrophages is crucial for clearing any particulate matter or pathogens that may enter the alveoli, but it does not directly contribute to keeping the alveoli dry.\r\n\r\nNegative interstitial fluid pressure is mainly involved in maintaining the structural integrity of the lungs and preventing alveolar collapse.\r\n\r\nHigh capillary hydrostatic pressure is more relevant to fluid movement within the capillaries.\r\n\r\nReduced pulmonary lymph flow would likely result in an accumulation of fluid in the interstitium, contributing to wet alveoli rather than keeping them dry.","reference":"Hall, John E., and Michael E. Hall. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed., Elsevier, 2020: 305.","responses":[{"text":"High capillary hydrostatic pressure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Negative interstitial fluid pressure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Reduced pulmonary lymph flow","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Phagocytic activity of alveolar macrophages","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Low vapor pressure of water in inspired air","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":21171,"text":"A patient has an episode of hematemesis (bloody vomiting). His Hb level is 11 gm/dl before the event of hematemesis. He is treated in a hospital. After 1 day, CBC report shows a Hb level of 10gm/dl. At this level of Hb, what is the oxygen-carrying capacity of his blood?","explanation":"To calculate the oxygen-carrying capacity of blood, the oxygen content can be estimated using the formula:\r\n\r\nOxygen content (mL/dL) = (Hb × 1.34 × SaO₂) + (0.0031 × PaO₂)\r\n​\r\nHowever, since the oxygen saturation (SaO₂) and partial pressure of oxygen (PaO₂) are not provided, we can use a simplified approximation based on the oxygen content solely related to hemoglobin:\r\n\r\n**Oxygen content (mL/dL) ≈ Hb × 1.34**\r\n\r\nNow, let's calculate the approximate oxygen-carrying capacity of blood at the Hb level of 10 gm/dl:\r\n\r\nOxygen content ≈ 10 x 1.34\r\n\r\nTherefore, at a hemoglobin level of 10 gm/dl, the approximate oxygen-carrying capacity of the blood is **13.4 mL/dL**.","reference":"Hall, John E., and Michael E. Hall. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed., Elsevier, 2020: 524.","responses":[{"text":"12.4","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"14.6","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"10.2","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"11.8","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"13.4","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":21172,"text":"Which of the following conditions leads to stagnant hypoxia?","explanation":"**Stagnant hypoxia** is a type of hypoxia that occurs when there is reduced blood flow or impaired circulation, leading to inadequate oxygen delivery to tissues despite normal oxygen content in the blood.\r\n\r\nIn **shock**, there is inadequate perfusion to tissues due to a decrease in effective blood volume or a failure in the circulatory system. **Heart failure**, especially left-sided heart failure, can lead to reduced cardiac output and inadequate circulation.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nCarbon monoxide (CO) poisoning reduces the oxygen-carrying capacity of hemoglobin by forming carboxyhemoglobin. However, it does not directly result in stagnant hypoxia; instead, it causes hypoxia by reducing the availability of functional hemoglobin for oxygen transport.\r\n\r\nCyanide poisoning inhibits cellular respiration at the mitochondrial level, leading to histotoxic hypoxia. It impairs the ability of cells to utilize oxygen for energy production.\r\n\r\nIron deficiency can lead to hypochromic microcytic anemia, reducing the oxygen-carrying capacity of hemoglobin. However, it does not cause stagnant hypoxia; rather, it results in a decreased ability of blood to carry oxygen.\r\n\r\nChronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD)  is characterized by airflow limitation and impaired gas exchange in the lungs, leading to hypoxic conditions. However, it does not directly cause stagnant hypoxia; instead, it is categorized as hypoxic hypoxia due to impaired oxygen exchange in the lungs.","reference":"Pittman, Roland N. “Oxygen Transport in Normal and Pathological Situations: Defects and Compensations.” Regulation of Tissue Oxygenation, Morgan \u0026 Claypool Life Sciences, 2011. www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov, https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK54113/.","responses":[{"text":"Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Iron deficiency state","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Shock and heart failure","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Cyanide poisoning","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"CO poisoning","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21173,"text":"A 45-year-old man has been experiencing chronic hypertension with muscle weakness and frequent muscle cramps despite lifestyle modifications and antihypertensive medications. On investigations, he is diagnosed with Conn's\r\nsyndrome (primary hyperaldosteronism). Which of the following biochemical characteristics is possible in this patient?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall, John E., and Michael E. Hall. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed., Elsevier, 2020: 415","responses":[{"text":"Decrease in the ratio of HCO3: H2CO3","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Disproportionate decrease in HCO3-","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Decrease in PCO2","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Increase in total CO content","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Decrease in H2CO3","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21174,"text":"A 47-year-old female presented to the emergency with a severe asthma attack, sweating, shortness of breath, fatigue, headache, drowsiness, and confusion. On examination, she is found hyperventilating, Her arterial blood gases report showed pH = 7.20, PaCO₂ = 58 mmHg, and HCO₃⁻ = 21 mEq/L. What is the provisional diagnosis of this patient based on ABGs?","explanation":"In **respiratory acidosis**, there is an accumulation of carbon dioxide (PaCO₂) in the blood, leading to a decrease in pH. Arterial blood gas analysis shows a **low pH** (7.20), **elevated PaCO₂** (58 mmHg), and a compensatory **decrease in bicarbonate** (HCO₃⁻) concentration. The hyperventilation in this case may be a compensatory response to try to eliminate excess carbon dioxide.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nMetabolic alkalosis is characterized by elevated pH and HCO₃⁻ levels.\r\n\r\nMetabolic acidosis is characterized by a low pH and low bicarbonate levels with normal PaCO₂.\r\n\r\nMixed acidosis/alkalosis is unlikely as the clinical presentation and ABGs suggest a single primary acid-base disturbance.\r\n\r\nRespiratory alkalosis is characterized by a low PaCO2 and an elevated pH.","reference":"Hall, John E., and Michael E. Hall. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed., Elsevier, 2020: 409","responses":[{"text":"Respiratory acidosis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Respiratory alkalosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Metabolic acidosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Metabolic alkalosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mixed acidosis/alkalosis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21185,"text":"A 1-day-old preterm neonate presented with complaints of tachypnea (Increased respiratory rate), respiratory distress, and cyanosis. A history of gestational diabetes mellitus was present in the mother. Which of the following is most likely\r\nfinding if the amniotic fluid was assessed after 34 weeks of gestation?","explanation":null,"reference":"Sattar, Husain A. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com, 2021: 95.","responses":[{"text":"Lecithin/sphingomyelin ratio of more than 2","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Lecithin/sphingomyelin ratio of less than 1","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lecithin/sphingomyelin ratio of less than 5","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lecithin/sphingomyelin ratio of more than 5","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lecithin/sphingomyelin ratio of less than 2","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21186,"text":"\"The enzyme responsible for the breakdown of phospholipids into fatty acids and glycerol\". The given explanation best corresponds to which of the following enzymes?","explanation":"**Lipases** are a group of enzymes that specialize in **hydrolyzing** ester bonds in lipids, including **phospholipids**. They cleave the fatty acid ester bonds in phospholipids, releasing fatty acids and glycerol.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nPhosphatidyl phosphorylase catalyzes the formation of phosphatidylglycerol from diacylglycerol and inorganic phosphate.\r\n\r\nPhosphatidyl kinase phosphorylates phosphatidylglycerol to phosphatidyldiglycerol, another step in phospholipid biosynthesis, not degradation.\r\n\r\nPhosphorylase breaks down glycogen into glucose-1-phosphate, not phospholipids.\r\n\r\nAmylase breaks down starch into glucose and maltose.","reference":"Rodwell, Victor W., et al. Harper’s Illustrated Biochemistry. 32nd ed., McGraw-Hill Education, 2022: 242.","responses":[{"text":"Amylase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Phosphorylase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Phosphatidyl kinase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Phosphatidyl phosphorylase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lipase","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":21187,"text":"Slow-reacting substances of anaphylaxis (SRS-A) are an important regulator in many diseases involving inflammatory or immediate hypersensitivity reactions such as asthma. Which of the following explanations best corresponds to slow-reacting substances of anaphylaxis?","explanation":"**Slow-reacting substances of anaphylaxis** (SRS-A) consist of leukotrienes, specifically **leukotriene C4**, leukotriene **E4**, and leukotriene **D4.** These are potent mediators of smooth muscle contraction, especially in the bronchioles, and play a key role in the pathophysiology of asthma and immediate hypersensitivity reactions.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nSRS-A is not a product of the cyclooxygenase pathway. It is derived from the lipoxygenase pathway.\r\n\r\nWhile SRS-A can have vasodilatory effects, the primary characteristic is related to their role in mediating bronchoconstriction and other effects associated with anaphylaxis.\r\n\r\nNSAIDs primarily inhibit the cyclooxygenase pathway, not the lipoxygenase pathway responsible for the synthesis of leukotrienes. Therefore, NSAIDs do not directly inhibit the effects of SRS-A.\r\n\r\nSRS-A is not an anti-inflammatory compound; instead, it contributes to the inflammatory response.","reference":"Rodwell, Victor W., et al. Harper’s Illustrated Biochemistry. 32nd ed., McGraw-Hill Education, 2022: 237","responses":[{"text":"Anti-inflammatory compound","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mixture of leukotrienes C4, E4, and D4","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Cyclooxygenase pathway product","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inhibited by NSAIDs","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vasodilator","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21188,"text":"Bicarbonate buffer is an effective physiological extracellular buffer comprising carbonic acid (the proton donor) and bicarbonate (the proton acceptor). Which of the following statements about bicarbonate and its effectiveness as a buffer is accurate?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall, John E., and Michael E. Hall. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed., Elsevier, 2020: 407.","responses":[{"text":"The bicarbonate buffer is most effective at a pH of 7.0, maintaining a neutral environment in the body","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The bicarbonate buffer is most effective at a pH of 6.1, corresponding to the pKa of carbonic acid","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Decreased activity of carbonic anhydrase leads to increased plasma bicarbonate concentration","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Carbonic anhydrase is the primary enzyme that catalyzes the formation of CO2 in the bicarbonate buffer system","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"A fall in physiological pH is associated with a state of primary bicarbonate deficit due to decreased plasma bicarbonate concentration","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21189,"text":"The presence of which of the following is the main difference between glycerophosphatides and phosphosphingoside?","explanation":"The main difference between glycerophospholipids (glycerophosphatides) and sphingolipids (phosphosphingosides) lies in their core structures.\r\n\r\n**Glycerophospholipids** have a **glycerol backbone** as their core structure.\r\nThey consist of two fatty acid chains attached to glycerol, a phosphate group, and a polar head group.\r\n\r\n**Sphingolipids**, on the other hand, consist of a **sphingosine backbone**, a fatty acid chain, a phosphate group, and a polar head group.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nLecithin is a type of glycerophospholipid, and it is not a specific difference between the two classes.\r\n\r\nPlasmalogens are a type of glycerophospholipid, not a specific difference.\r\n\r\nLipositol does not specifically refer to a core structure of either glycerophospholipids or sphingolipids.\r\n\r\nPhosphatides is a general term for both glycerophospholipids and sphingolipids.","reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2020: 202.","responses":[{"text":"Plasmalogens","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lecithin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Phosphatides","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sphingosine","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Lipositol","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21190,"text":"A 32-year-old man is found unresponsive on the street and brought to the emergency department. Emergency personnel found what is presumed to be heroin and a syringe near his body. He is lethargic and cyanotic with symmetric pinpoint pupils. Vital signs are temperature 36.0°C (96.8°F); heart rate 70/min; respiratory rate 6/min; and blood pressure 100/60 mmHg. An arterial blood gas sample (ABG) is drawn in addition to the following laboratory tests:\r\nSerum Na+ = 138 mEq/L\r\nSerum Cl- = 101 mEq/L.\r\nSerum K+ = 4.0 mEq/L\r\nSerum creatinine (SCr) = 0.58 mg/dl.\r\n\r\nWhat would most likely be seen on this patient's ABG?","explanation":"Lethargy, cyanosis, symmetric pinpoint pupils, and respiratory depression, along with the presence of presumed heroin and a syringe, suggest **opioid intoxication**. Opioids, such as heroin, can cause respiratory depression, leading to hypoventilation and subsequent respiratory acidosis. The most likely arterial blood gas (ABG) findings are given below.\r\n\r\n- Increased PCO₂: Inadequate ventilation leads to an accumulation of carbon dioxide (CO₂).\r\n- Decreased pH: Increased  PCO₂ leads to a subsequent increase in carbonic acid levels, resulting in a decreased pH and respiratory acidosis.\r\n- Increased HCO₃⁻: In chronic respiratory acidosis, the kidneys compensate by retaining bicarbonate (HCO3-) to maintain acid-base balance.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nDecreased pH, decreased PCO₂, and decreased HCO₃⁻ are more indicative of metabolic acidosis, which is not the primary acid-base disturbance in opioid intoxication.","reference":"Hall, John E., and Michael E. Hall. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed., Elsevier, 2020: 409","responses":[{"text":"Normal pH; increased PCO2; increased HCO3-","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Decreased pH; decreased PCO2; decreased HCO3-","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased pH; decreased PCO2; decreased HCO3-","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Decreased pH; increased PCO2; increased HCO3-","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased pH; increased PCO2; increased HCO3-","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21191,"text":"A 35-year-old man has chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) and has elevated levels of carbon dioxide in his blood, resulting in respiratory acidosis. How would his body attempt to compensate for this respiratory acidosis?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall, John E., and Michael E. Hall. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed., Elsevier, 2020: 415","responses":[{"text":"The bicarbonate buffer system releases more bicarbonate ions","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"The respiratory rate increases to expel more carbon dioxide","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Patient's blood becomes more alkaline","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The kidneys excrete excess bicarbonate ions","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The kidneys will absorb H+ ions","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21192,"text":"Which of the following is the least characteristic of asthma?","explanation":"While immunoglobulins play a role in immune responses, an increase in IgG immunoglobulins is not a prominent feature of **asthma**. Asthma is primarily associated with type 2 hypersensitivity reactions, where **immunoglobulin E** (IgE), not IgG, plays a key role.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nAsthma is often associated with airway inflammation, and the infiltration of eosinophils into the airway is a characteristic feature. Eosinophils release inflammatory mediators contributing to the pathogenesis of asthma.\r\n\r\nThe airways produce excess mucus in response to inflammation and irritants, contributing to airway obstruction in asthma.\r\n\r\nMast cell activation and degranulation are crucial features of asthma. IgE-mediated activation of mast cells leads to the release of inflammatory mediators, contributing to bronchoconstriction and inflammation.\r\n\r\nAirway hyperresponsiveness, where the airways are more sensitive to various stimuli, is a hallmark of asthma. It leads to exaggerated bronchoconstriction in response to triggers.","reference":"Sattar, Husain A. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com, 2021: 91.","responses":[{"text":"Infiltration of eosinophils in the airway","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mast cell activation and degranulation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Airway hyperresponsiveness","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased mucus production","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increase in IgG immunoglobulins","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":21194,"text":"Which of the following congenital diseases affecting the lungs is most common?","explanation":null,"reference":"Moore, Keith L., et al. The Developing Human: Clinically Oriented Embryology. 11th ed., Saunders/Elsevier, 2020: 198.","responses":[{"text":"Congenital diaphragmatic hernia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pleural effusion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Marfan's disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lack of pulmonary surfactant protein B","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tracheo-oesophageal fistula","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":21210,"text":"A 50-year-old man (a known patient with rhinitis and polyps) presents to your clinic with a history of repeated asthma attacks and urticaria. On further inquiry, she reports taking aspirin for her lower back pain. What is the most likely cause of her asthma attacks?","explanation":"**Aspirin-exacerbated respiratory disease** (AERD), aspirin, and other nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs) can trigger asthma attacks by increasing the production of **leukotrienes**, leading to bronchoconstriction.\r\n\r\nThe patient's intake of aspirin for back pain coincides with the reported asthma attacks, suggesting a potential causative link. This diagnosis is further supported by the presence of rhinitis and polyps, which are classically associated with AERD. \r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nNasal polyps and rhinitis are associated with (AERD), but a predisposition to necrotizing bronchial infections is not a feature of AERD.\r\n\r\nAERD is associated with bronchoconstriction, not dilation of the airways.\r\n\r\nWhile nasal polyps are associated with aspirin-exacerbated respiratory disease (AERD), the presence of nasal polyps does not necessarily mean the individual will have polyps in the lungs.\r\n\r\nWhile a positive family history is a risk factor for asthma, the information provided does not suggest that her asthma attacks are primarily due to a positive family history.","reference":"Sattar, Husain A. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com, 2021: 85.","responses":[{"text":"Aspirin damages her distal airways causing them to dilate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Polyps in her nose also cause her to have polyps in her lungs","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"She most likely has a positive family history for asthma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aspirin causes increased leukotrienes production which causes bronchospasm","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Nasal polyps and rhinitis predispose her to necrotizing bronchial infections","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21211,"text":"Asthma is a common obstructive lung disease. It is characterized by which of the following pathological changes?","explanation":"**Asthma** is primarily characterized by inflammation of the airways, leading to increased **mucus** production, **smooth muscle hyperplasia** (thickening of the airway walls due to increased smooth muscle mass), and **inflammatory** cell infiltration. These changes contribute to airway narrowing and bronchoconstriction.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nAirspace enlargement and wall destruction without obvious fibrosis are more characteristic of emphysema.\r\n\r\nInflammatory scarring and obliteration are more in line with bronchiolitis obliterans, a condition involving inflammation, fibrosis, and obliteration of small airways.\r\n\r\nAirway dilatation and scarring are more characteristic of bronchiectasis.\r\n\r\nNecrotizing inflammation and extensive fibrosis are more characteristic of diseases such as granulomatosis with polyangiitis.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 678. Table 15.3.","responses":[{"text":"Airway dilatation and scarring","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Necrotizing inflammation and fibrosis of airway walls","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Smooth muscle hyperplasia, excess mucus and inflammation","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Airspace enlargement and wall destruction with no obvious fibrosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inflammatory scarring and obliteration","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21212,"text":"Which of the following statement is correct about the lung diseases?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall, John E., and Michael E. Hall. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed., Elsevier, 2020: 543.","responses":[{"text":"Restrictive lung diseases are characterized by reduced expansion of the lung","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Obstructive lung diseases are characterized by limitation to air flow","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Obstructive lung diseases are characterized by reduced expansion of the lung","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Restrictive lung diseases are characterized by limitation to air flow","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Restrictive lung diseases are characterized by reduced expiratory flow rate","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21213,"text":"Which of the following is the most appropriate regarding community-acquired pneumonia?","explanation":"**Young children** (\u003c5 years) and **older adults** (\u003e65 years) are considered to be at higher risk for **community-acquired pneumonia**. Immature or weakened immune systems in children and age-related decline in immune function in older adults contribute to increased susceptibility.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nHemoptysis (coughing up blood) is not always a symptom of community-acquired pneumonia. Symptoms can vary and may include cough, fever, shortness of breath, and chest pain, among others.\r\n\r\nCommunity-acquired pneumonia can present with different patterns, including bronchopneumonia and lobar pneumonia. The presentation may vary based on the causative organism and the affected population.\r\n\r\nPleurisy (inflammation of the lining of the lungs) is not always a consistent symptom of community-acquired pneumonia.\r\n\r\nWhile gram-negative bacteria can cause pneumonia, the most common causative organisms for community-acquired pneumonia are typically *Streptococcus pneumoniae*, *Haemophilus influenzae*, and atypical bacteria such as *Mycoplasma pneumoniae*.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 706-709.","responses":[{"text":"It mostly presents like bronchopneumonia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Risk factors include \u003c5 and \u003e65 age","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"The most frequently identified organisms are gram-negative","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Symptoms always include hemoptysis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Symptoms always include pleurisy","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21214,"text":"A 75-year-old man has been hospitalized for the past 1 week with COVID-19 pneumonia. He develops sudden onset dyspnea and tachypnea. His lips appear blue and his oxygen saturation drops drastically. Chest x-ray shows diffuse bilateral infiltrates (white lung). What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"**Acute respiratory distress syndrome** (ARDS) is a severe form of acute lung injury that can be triggered by various conditions, including **viral pneumonia** such as COVID-19. The sudden onset of dyspnea, tachypnea, blue lips (cyanosis), and a drop in oxygen saturation are characteristic features. Diffuse bilateral infiltrates on chest X-rays are common findings in ARDS.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nFat embolism typically occurs after long bone fractures or trauma.\r\n\r\nMiliary tuberculosis can cause respiratory symptoms, but the sudden onset dyspnea, tachypnea, and \"white lung\" appearance on chest X-ray are more suggestive of ARDS.\r\n\r\nAcute on chronic bronchitis is less likely to cause sudden onset dyspnea and drastic drops in oxygen saturation. It is more commonly associated with chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD).\r\n\r\nWhile septicemia can cause respiratory distress, the specific findings of \"white lung\" on chest X-ray are more indicative of ARDS, which can be a complication of severe infections, including COVID-19 pneumonia.","reference":"Sattar, Husain A. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com, 2021: 94.","responses":[{"text":"Miliary tuberculosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fat embolism","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute on chronic bronchitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute respiratory distress syndrome","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Septicemia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21215,"text":"A 22-year-old female presents with a persistent cough, low-grade fever, and unintentional weight loss of 5 for the past three months. She reports occasional night sweats and a family history of TB. On physical examination, lymph nodes are palpable and there are decreased breath sounds over the right upper lung field. A chest X-ray reveals a cavitary lesion in the right upper lobe. A fine needle aspiration is performed on the lymph nodes and pus is aspirated. What is the underlying process behind this pus formation?","explanation":"**Caseous necrosis** is a type of necrosis characterized by a soft and granular appearance resembling clumped cheese. It is often associated with granulomatous inflammation. It is a characteristic feature of **tuberculosis** (TB), and the cavitary lesions observed in the lung are often filled with necrotic material.\r\n\r\nCavitary lesions are a characteristic feature of advanced pulmonary TB. Patients often present with a persistent cough, low-grade fever, unintentional weight loss, and occasional night sweats. This diagnosis is further supported by the patient's family history, which is positive for tuberculosis.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nCoagulative necrosis is a type of necrosis characterized by protein denaturation, which usually occurs in ischemic conditions such as infarction.\r\n\r\nApoptosis refers to programmed cell death that does not typically result in the formation of pus. It is a controlled process of cellular dismantling.\r\n\r\nFibrinoid necrosis is a type of necrosis characterized by deposition of fibrin-like material in the walls of arteries or arterioles, often seen in immune-mediated vasculitis. \r\n\r\nLiquefactive necrosis is characterized by the transformation of tissue into a liquid viscous mass.","reference":"Kumar, Vinay, et al. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed., Elsevier, 2020: 41.","responses":[{"text":"Caseous necrosis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Fibrinoid necrosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Coagulative necrosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Liquefactive necrosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Apoptosis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21216,"text":"A 35-year-old male presents with a persistent cough, low-grade fever, and night sweats for the past two months. He reports a history of working in a homeless shelter. Physical examination is unremarkable except for mild cervical lymphadenopathy. A chest X-ray shows infiltrates in the right upper lobe. Acid-fast staining of sputum confirms the presence of acid-fast bacilli. Which of the following mechanisms best explains the early events in the infection?","explanation":"Upon inhalation, the ***Mycobacterium tuberculosis*** bacteria are engulfed by alveolar macrophages, which are immune cells responsible for clearing pathogens in the lungs. However, *M. tuberculosis* has developed mechanisms to **survive** and replicate within these macrophages. Instead of being destroyed, the bacteria can persist and even multiply **within the phagosomes of macrophages**.\r\n\r\nThe formation of granulomas, organized structures composed of immune cells, is a subsequent immune response to contain the infection. Granulomas play a role in limiting bacterial spread but can also serve as a site for latent infection, where the bacteria remain dormant for an extended period.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\n*M. tuberculosis* does not invade and replicate within red blood cells. Its primary target is alveolar macrophages in the lungs.\r\n\r\nM. tuberculosis does not produce exotoxins that cause tissue damage. The pathology is more related to the immune response and the formation of granulomas.\r\n\r\nWhile abscesses can form in bacterial lung infections, it is not a typical feature of early tuberculosis.\r\n\r\n*M. tuberculosis* does not form encapsulated cysts.","reference":"Kumar, Vinay, et al. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed., Elsevier, 2020: 341.","responses":[{"text":"Formation of abscesses in lung tissue","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Production of exotoxins causing tissue damage","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intracellular survival within alveolar macrophages","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Invasion and replication within RBCs","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Development of encapsulated cysts in lung parenchyma","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21217,"text":"A 28-year-old healthcare worker, recently exposed to a patient with confirmed\r\n pulmonary tuberculosis, is concerned about possible infection. She undergoes a Mantoux tuberculin skin test. Two days later, the test site revealed a 12 mm induration. What mechanism best explains the positive result of the Mantoux test?","explanation":"The **Mantoux test** is a type of **delayed-type hypersensitivity reaction**, reflecting a cell-mediated immune response against *Mycobacterium tuberculosis* antigens. Sensitized T cells that were previously exposed to *M. tuberculosis* antigens will migrate to the injection site, leading to an inflammatory response and induration.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nThe Mantoux test involves the intradermal injection of purified protein derivative (PPD) of tuberculin, not direct mycobacterial antigens.\r\n\r\nThe Mantoux test primarily measures a hypersensitivity reaction mediated by T cells. It is not focused on antibody production by B cells.\r\n\r\nThe Mantoux test does not elicit an immediate hypersensitivity reaction. The positive response takes time to develop and is characterized by induration at the injection site.\r\n\r\nThe mechanism of the Mantoux test is not based on the activation of neutrophils or tissue destruction. Instead, it measures the delayed hypersensitivity reaction mediated by T cells.","reference":"Kumar, Vinay, et al. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed., Elsevier, 2020: 371.","responses":[{"text":"Delayed-type hypersensitivity reaction to tuberculin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Direct activation of mycobacterial antigens in the skin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Activation of B cells and antibody production against TB","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Activation of neutrophils and tissue destruction","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Immediate hypersensitivity to purified protein derivative (PPD)","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21218,"text":"A 6-week-old infant presents with severe paroxysms of coughing and whooping sounds, along with posttussive emesis. The patient has not received any vaccinations yet. Bordetella pertussis infection is suspected and the patient is treated with antibiotics. Pertussis toxin, a known virulence factor of Bordetella Pertussis plays a crucial role in the pathogenesis of the disease. What is the mechanism of action of this toxin?","explanation":"**Pertussis toxin** is an **ADP-ribosylating** toxin that modifies G proteins, specifically inhibiting the function of **G proteins** (Gi). This results in increased adenylyl cyclase activity and subsequent elevation of intracellular cyclic AMP (cAMP). The **increased cAMP** levels disrupt cellular signaling and contribute to the pathogenesis of pertussis.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nPertussis toxin does stimulate the production of antibodies, but its primary mechanism of action is not the induction of toxin-neutralizing antibodies. Instead, it interferes with cellular signaling.\r\n\r\nPertussis toxin is not involved in inhibiting bacterial adhesion.\r\n\r\nBlockade of histamine release from mast cells is associated with tracheal cytotoxin, not pertussis toxin.\r\n\r\nNeutrophil chemotaxis is not the primary target of pertussis toxin.","reference":"Kumar, Vinay, et al. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed., Elsevier, 2020: 365.","responses":[{"text":"Inhibition of neutrophil chemotaxis to the site of infection","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Induction of toxin-neutralizing antibodies","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inhibition of bacterial adhesion to respiratory epithelium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"ADP-ribosylation of G proteins, leading to increased cAMP production","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Blockade of histamine release from mast cells","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21220,"text":"A 37-year-old male with a history of chronic obstructive pulmonary disease presents with high fever, cough, and confusion. He is admitted to the hospital and a chest X-ray reveals multifocal, patchy consolidation. A diagnosis of atypical pneumonia is made. On probing, he provides a history of attending a meeting during the last week. Which of the following is the most likely cause of his illness?","explanation":"***Legionella pneumophila*** is associated with Legionnaires disease, a severe form of atypical pneumonia. It often presents with high fever, cough, confusion, and chest X-ray findings of multifocal, patchy consolidation. Legionella is commonly associated with contaminated water sources such as air conditioning systems, hot tubs, and cooling towers.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\n*Pseudomonas aeruginosa* is a bacterium that can cause pneumonia, especially in immunocompromised individuals or those with chronic lung diseases. However, the clinical presentation with patchy consolidation and association with attending a meeting are more suggestive of Legionella pneumonia.\r\n\r\n*Streptococcus pneumoniae* is a common cause of typical, not atypical, community-acquired pneumonia.\r\n\r\n*Klebsiella pneumoniae* can cause pneumonia, often characterized by a rapid and destructive course. However, it is not typically associated with community-acquired pneumonia and is often linked to healthcare-associated infections.\r\n\r\n*Staphylococcus aureus* can cause pneumonia, but its involvement is often associated with healthcare-associated pneumonia","reference":"Kumar, Vinay, et al. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed., Elsevier, 2020: 707.","responses":[{"text":"Klebsiella pneumoniae","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Staphylococcus aureus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Streptococcus pneumonia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Legionella pneumophilia","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pseudomonas aeriguinosa","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21231,"text":"A previously healthy 12-month-old child presents with fever, cough, and increased respiratory effort. A chest X-ray reveals a right lower lobe consolidation with pleural effusion. Sputum culture grows gram-negative coccobacillary rods on chocolate agar. What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"***Hemophilus influenzae***, is a gram-negative coccobacillary rod that grows on **chocolate agar**.\r\n\r\nHemophilus influenzae particularly type b (Hib), is a common cause of bacterial **pneumonia** in young children. It can present with fever, cough, and respiratory distress. The development of consolidation in the lower lobe of a lung with pleural effusion is consistent with severe pneumonia.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\n*Klebsiella pneumoniae* istypically associated with pneumonia in individuals with underlying health conditions. It is not a common cause of pneumonia in a previously healthy child.\r\n\r\n*Acinetobacter* is often associated with nosocomial infections.\r\n\r\n*Legionella pneumophila* is associated with Legionnaires disease, which presents with severe pneumonia. However, it is less common in young children, and the described findings are not typical of Legionnaires disease.\r\n\r\n*Pseudomonas aeruginosa* is associated with severe infections, but it is not a common cause of pneumonia, especially in healthy infants.","reference":"Kumar, Vinay, et al. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed., Elsevier, 2020: 706","responses":[{"text":"Actinobacter","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pseudomonas aeruginosa","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemophilus influenzae","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Legionella pneumophilia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Klebsiella pneumonia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21232,"text":"A 40-year-old male, obese, smoker underwent surgery for a femur fracture. He stayed in the hospital for one week and was on anticoagulant therapy. At home, he suddenly developed dyspnea and cyanosis. He was taken to the hospital but could not survive. Which risk factor is least likely to be associated with his cause of death?","explanation":null,"reference":"Cukic V, Baljic R. The most common detected risk and etiologic factors of pulmonary thromboembolism. Materia Socio-Medica. Published 2012. Accessed December 28, 2023. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3732340/","responses":[{"text":"Immobility","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Recent surgery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Obesity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Age","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Smoking","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":21233,"text":"A 35-year-old male with a severe, persistent cough, and expectoration of foul-smelling sputum, particularly frequent when the patient rises in the morning. He also has a history of chronic sinusitis. On chest X-ray, bronchi are dilated, bronchovascular markings are increased, pulmonary vasculature appears ill-defined, representing fibrosis. What are the conditions that predispose to this disease?","explanation":"**Kartagener syndrome** is a subset of **primary ciliary dyskinesia** (PCD), a genetic disorder affecting ciliary structure and function. It is characterized by chronic respiratory infections, bronchiectasis, chronic sinusitis, and situs inversus, where the major visceral organs are reversed or mirrored from their normal positions. The impaired ciliary function leads to difficulty in clearing mucus and debris from the respiratory tract.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nAtopic individuals may have allergic conditions such as asthma or allergic rhinitis, but the described symptoms and radiographic findings, including bronchiectasis and fibrosis, are not typical of atopic conditions.\r\n\r\nWhile obesity can contribute to respiratory issues and may be associated with conditions such as obstructive sleep apnea, fibrosis is not typical of obesity-related respiratory diseases.\r\n\r\nAlpha-1 antitrypsin deficiency primarily predisposes individuals to early-onset emphysema rather than bronchiectasis.\r\n\r\nSmoking is a significant risk factor for the development of chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) and emphysema, but the specific findings mentioned, including dilated bronchi, increased bronchovascular markings, and ill-defined pulmonary vasculature with fibrosis, are not typical of smoking-related lung diseases.","reference":"Kumar, Vinay, et al. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed., Elsevier, 2020: 687-688.","responses":[{"text":"Smoking","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Congenital alpha-1 anti trypsin deficiency","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Atopic individual","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Kartagener's syndrome","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Obesity","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21234,"text":"Which one of the following is a feature of Kartagener syndrome?","explanation":"**Cor pulmonale** refers to right-sided heart failure resulting from pulmonary hypertension. In **Kartagener syndrome**, the impaired function of cilia can lead to chronic respiratory infections and bronchiectasis, contributing to the development of pulmonary hypertension and cor pulmonale.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nEmphysema is not a typical feature of Kartagener syndrome. The primary manifestations are related to ciliary dysfunction, leading to recurrent respiratory infections, sinusitis, and bronchiectasis.\r\n\r\nKartagener syndrome is an autosomal recessive, not dominant, genetic disorder.\r\n\r\nBronchospasm and atypical metaplasia are not primary features of Kartagener syndrome.","reference":"Kumar, Vinay, et al. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed., Elsevier, 2020: 556","responses":[{"text":"Emphysema","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Autosomal dominant","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bronchospasm","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cor pulmonale","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Atypical metaplasia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21235,"text":"Due to its anti-inflammatory mechanism of action, which of the following medications require regular administration for the treatment of asthma?","explanation":"**Beclomethasone** is an inhaled corticosteroid (ICS) that has potent anti-inflammatory effects. It is used for the long-term management of asthma to control inflammation and prevent exacerbations. **Regular administration** is crucial for its effectiveness in managing chronic airway inflammation.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nSalbutamol (also known as albuterol) is a short-acting beta-agonist (SABA) primarily used for quick relief of acute bronchoconstriction. While it helps with bronchodilation, it is not a medication for regular, long-term anti-inflammatory control of asthma.\r\n\r\nTiotropium is a long-acting anticholinergic bronchodilator. While it helps with bronchodilation, it is not specifically an anti-inflammatory medication. It is used for the maintenance treatment of chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) and, in some cases, asthma.\r\n\r\nSalmeterol is a long-acting beta-agonist (LABA) that provides bronchodilation but does not have significant anti-inflammatory effects.","reference":"Katzung BG, Todd W. Vanderah. Basic and Clinical Pharmacology. 15th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2021: 354-355.","responses":[{"text":"Tiotropium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Beclomethasone","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Salmoterol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Albuterol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Salbutamol","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21236,"text":"Oral medications are popular for the treatment of asthma in children because young children may have difficulty with the proper use of aerosol inhalers. Which of the following is an orally active inhibitor of 5-lipoxygenase enzyme to inhibit leukotrienes?","explanation":"**Zileuton** is an **orally active** inhibitor of 5-lipoxygenase, which is involved in the synthesis of leukotrienes. Leukotrienes play a role in the inflammatory process associated with asthma. By **inhibiting 5-lipoxygenase**, zileuton helps reduce leukotriene production.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nAminophylline is a bronchodilator that belongs to the methylxanthine class. It works by inhibiting phosphodiesterase and adenosine receptors, leading to bronchodilation.\r\n\r\nAlbuterol is a short-acting beta-agonist that primarily acts as a bronchodilator by stimulating beta-2 adrenergic receptors.\r\n\r\nIpratropium is an anticholinergic bronchodilator that works by blocking muscarinic receptors.\r\n\r\nMontelukast is a leukotriene receptor antagonist that works by blocking the action of leukotrienes at the receptor level.","reference":"Katzung BG, Todd W. Vanderah. Basic and Clinical Pharmacology. 15th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2021: 356.","responses":[{"text":"Zileuton","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Aminophylline","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ipratropium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Albuterol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Montelukast","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21238,"text":"A patient is advised to take antitubercular therapy for six months. After 12 weeks of treatment, the patient complains of visual defects. Which drug is responsible for this side effect?","explanation":"**Visual disturbances**, including optic neuritis and color blindness, are known adverse effects of **ethambutol**. These ocular adverse effects are dose-related and occur more frequently with higher doses and prolonged therapy. Patients on ethambutol should undergo regular ophthalmologic monitoring to detect visual changes early.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nStreptomycin is primarily associated with ototoxicity and vestibular toxicity.\r\n\r\nIsoniazid is known for causing peripheral neuropathy, particularly in individuals with low levels of vitamin B6.\r\n\r\nRifampin is associated with potential hepatotoxicity and induction of cytochrome P450 enzymes.\r\n\r\nPyrazinamide is more commonly associated with hepatotoxicity and hyperuricemia.","reference":"Katzung BG, Todd W. Vanderah. Basic and Clinical Pharmacology. 15th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2021: 845-846.","responses":[{"text":"Pyrizinamide","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Streptomycin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rifampin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Isoniazid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ethambutol","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":21239,"text":"A 49-year-old cobbler contracts severe diarrhea due to cholera. He used to drink and eat from the roadside hotels. He has a low BMI with a history of hypertension, and his personal hygiene is poor. He lives in a small space with many other workers. In the above scenario, what is the primary determinant of his acute illness?","explanation":"The cobbler's living conditions, including drinking and eating from roadside hotels, poor personal hygiene, and living in a crowded space with other workers, are indicative of impoverished circumstances. **Poverty** is often associated with inadequate access to clean water, sanitation, and healthcare, increasing the risk of infectious diseases like cholera.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nPersonal hygiene is a contributing factor to the risk of infectious diseases, including cholera. However, in this scenario, poverty encompasses multiple aspects, including poor personal hygiene, making poverty a broader determinant of acute illness.\r\n\r\nPoor nutrition may contribute to an individual's overall health, but in this scenario, the focus is on the acute illness caused by severe diarrhea due to cholera. While poor nutrition can weaken the immune system, the primary determinant in this case is related to the immediate cause of the illness.\r\n\r\nCholera is an infectious disease and is not associated with diabetes.\r\n\r\nBacteria are the causative agents of cholera, but in this case, the broader socio-economic factors, such as poverty, play a more significant role.","reference":"Dow Lecture Slides, Respiratory Module, Community Medicine. Lecture: Origin and Determinants of Disease.","responses":[{"text":"Poor nutrition","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Diabetes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bacteria","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Personal hygiene","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Poverty","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":21240,"text":"A young mother was informed by the birth attendant that her recently born firstborn baby has trisomy 21. The reason for the above-mentioned disease lies at what stage?","explanation":"**Trisomy 21** is a chromosomal disorder characterized by the presence of an extra copy of chromosome 21. This additional chromosome usually results from nondisjunction during the process of **fertilization**.\r\n\r\nWhen the sperm fertilizes the egg, the resulting zygote should normally have 46 chromosomes, with 23 from each parent. In cases of trisomy 21, an error occurs during cell division, leading to the presence of an extra copy of chromosome 21, resulting in a total of 47 chromosomes instead of the usual 46.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nWhile the presence of an additional chromosome can affect various organ systems, the root cause is the chromosomal abnormality.\r\n\r\nThe chromosomal abnormality is established during fertilization and exists in the zygote from the early stages of embryonic development. It is not related to the later stages of growth and development just before or immediately after childbirth.\r\n\r\nWhile the placenta plays a crucial role in pregnancy, it is not the origin of trisomy 21.","reference":"Dow Lecture Slides, Respiratory Module, Community Medicine. Lecture: Origin and Determinants of Disease.","responses":[{"text":"First hour after birth","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Organ development","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Placenta development","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Just before the childbirth","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fertilization","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":21243,"text":"A type of learning in which a neutral stimulus is presented repeatedly with one that reflexively elicits a particular response so that the neutral stimulus eventually elicits the response itself is known as classical conditioning. After a certain time, the response becomes extinct but it can re-emerge after a period of time has passed with no further conditioning. What is the name for this phenomenon?","explanation":"**Spontaneous recovery** is a phenomenon in classical conditioning where a previously **extinguished response re-emerges** after some time has passed **without further conditioning**.\r\n\r\nIn classical conditioning, a neutral stimulus (initially having no intrinsic meaning) is repeatedly paired with an unconditioned stimulus, which naturally elicits a reflexive response. Over time, the neutral stimulus becomes a conditioned stimulus, capable of eliciting the response on its own.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nOperant conditioning involves learning through consequences, where behavior is strengthened or weakened based on reinforcement or punishment. In operant conditioning, the focus is more on the consequences that follow a behavior.\r\n\r\nLearning is a broader term encompassing various types of associative processes, including classical and operant conditioning. The question is more specifically addressing the re-emergence of a previously extinguished response.\r\n\r\nExtinction is the process in classical conditioning where a conditioned response decreases or disappears when the conditioned stimulus is presented without the unconditioned stimulus. It does not, however, directly address the re-emergence of the response after a period.\r\n\r\nStimulus generalization occurs when a conditioned response is elicited by stimuli similar to the conditioned stimulus.","reference":"Sissons, Heather T., and Ralph R. Miller. “Spontaneous Recovery of Excitation and Inhibition.” Journal of Experimental Psychology. Animal Behavior Processes, vol. 35, no. 3, July 2009, pp. 419–26. PubMed Central, https://doi.org/10.1037/a0014815.","responses":[{"text":"Operant conditioning","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Learning","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stimulus generalization","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Extinction","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Spontaneous recovery","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":21244,"text":"Sarah is in a bad mood and forcefully smiles for 10 seconds. This behavior can be explained by the facial feedback hypothesis. Which of the following does this hypothesis suggest?","explanation":"According to the **facial feedback hypothesis**, the act of moving facial muscles to make a **facial expression**, such as smiling or frowning, can influence and even trigger the associated emotions. In Sarah's case, her forceful smile may, to some extent, **influence** her **mood** or emotional state.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\n\"Once we know how we are feeling, we can change our facial expression.\" This statement is more aligned with the idea that our emotions influence our facial expressions, not the other way around. The facial feedback hypothesis emphasizes the impact of facial expressions on emotions, not just the reverse.\r\n\r\n\"We can judge someone else's mood by looking at their face.\" This statement pertains to the ability to infer emotions in others based on their facial expressions, which is related to emotional intelligence but is not the central focus of the facial feedback hypothesis.\r\n\r\n\"Some people disguise their emotions if they look in a mirror.\" The facial feedback hypothesis does not specifically address the act of disguising emotions in a mirror. It is more concerned with the bidirectional relationship between facial expressions and emotions.","reference":"Söderkvist, Sven, et al. “How the Experience of Emotion Is Modulated by Facial Feedback.” Journal of Nonverbal Behavior, vol. 42, no. 1, 2018, pp. 129–51. PubMed Central, https://doi.org/10.1007/s10919-017-0264-1.","responses":[{"text":"None of the above","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Once we know how we are feeling, we can change our facial expression","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Some people disguise their emotions if they look in a mirror","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The movement of our facial muscles can trigger emotions","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"We can judge someone else's mood by looking at their face","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21245,"text":"The pulmonary function test of a 40-year-old male showed the following values:\r\nFEV1/FVC- 65% of predicted\r\nTLC- Normal\r\nFVC- Normal\r\nDLCO- Low\r\nWhat would be the most likely diagnosis from this PFT?","explanation":"A decreased FEV1/FVC ratio, normal total lung capacity (TLC), normal forced vital capacity (FVC), and low decreased diffusion capacity of the lung for carbon monoxide (DLCO) are indicative of **emphysema**.\r\n\r\nThe forced vital capacity (**FVC**) being **normal** suggests that the individual can exhale forcefully, but the **reduced FEV1/FVC ratio** indicates airflow limitation during forced expiration, which is typically observed in cases with obstructive lung diseases such as emphysema.\r\n\r\nA decreased diffusion capacity of the lung for carbon monoxide (DLCO) is also associated with emphysema. The reduced surface area for gas exchange in damaged alveoli contributes to a **lower DLCO**.\r\n\r\nTLC is typically normal.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nChronic bronchitis typically shows a normal or increased FEV1/FVC ratio, distinguishing it from emphysema.\r\n\r\nInterstitial lung diseases present with restrictive patterns on PFTs, involving reduced lung volumes (TLC, FVC) and a preserved or increased FEV1/FVC ratio. The normal TLC in the provided case rules out interstitial lung disease.\r\n\r\nAsthma is characterized by reversible airflow obstruction. PFTs in asthma may show a decreased FEV1/FVC ratio during an exacerbation, but it should improve significantly after bronchodilator use, differentiating it from the irreversible airflow limitation seen in emphysema.\r\n\r\nSarcoidosis may present with restrictive lung disease patterns, showing reduced lung volumes and a preserved or increased FEV1/FVC ratio. It is less commonly associated with the obstructive pattern seen in emphysema.","reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 489.","responses":[{"text":"Sarcoidosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Emphysema","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Chronic bronchitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Interstitial lung disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Asthma","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21248,"text":"A 13-year-old female presents to the outpatient department with complaints of off-and-on shortness of breath for the last few years, especially during winters along with whistling sounds. Which of the following findings on the chest examination would be the most appropriate?","explanation":"Off-and-on shortness of breath, especially during winter, in a young patient is highly suggestive of asthma. **Asthma** is characterized by airway hyperresponsiveness, inflammation, and reversible airflow obstruction. **Bilateral wheezes** strongly suggest airway obstruction, which aligns with the typical presentation of asthma.\r\n\r\nWheezing is characterized by high-pitched, musical sounds during expiration and sometimes inspiration. It results from turbulent airflow through narrowed airways, a common feature in asthma.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nDecreased chest expansion may be associated with conditions such as pleural effusion or atelectasis, which are characterized by restriction rather than obstruction.\r\n\r\nA barrel-shaped chest is more characteristic of chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD), which typically affects older individuals with a history of smoking.\r\n\r\nIncreased percussion notes and bronchial breath sounds are not specific to asthma.","reference":"(1) Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 500.\r\n\r\n(2) Kumar, Vinay, et al. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed., Elsevier, 2020: 683.","responses":[{"text":"Barrel shaped chest on infection","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased percussion note","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Decreased chest expansion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bilateral wheezes on auscultation","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Bronchial breath sounds on examination","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21249,"text":"Which one of the following is an example of a post-contrast CT chest?","explanation":"**Post-contrast computed tomography** (CT) chest is commonly used in the **staging of cancer**, particularly those affecting the lungs or surrounding structures. Contrast enhancement helps in visualizing and characterizing lesions, evaluating lymph node involvement, and determining the extent of the disease.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nWhile the initial characterization of a mass may involve contrast-enhanced imaging, the biopsy itself is not specifically dependent on contrast.\r\n\r\nA post-traumatic patient may undergo CT imaging, but the use of contrast depends on the specific clinical indication. Not all post-traumatic cases necessitate contrast-enhanced imaging.\r\n\r\nEvaluation of interstitial lung disease typically involves high-resolution CT without the need for intravenous contrast.\r\n\r\nImaging findings associated with COVID pneumonia are often assessed without the use of intravenous contrast.","reference":"Li, Xili, et al. “Contrast-Enhanced Chest Computed Tomography (CT) Scan with Low Radiation and Total Iodine Dose for Lung Cancer Detection Using Adaptive Statistical Iterative Reconstruction.” Iranian Journal of Radiology, vol. 19, no. 4, 2022. brieflands.com, https://doi.org/10.5812/iranjradiol-126572.","responses":[{"text":"Post-traumatic patient","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Suspected covid pneumonia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Staging of cancer","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Interstitial lung disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Biopsy of lung/pleural mass","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21251,"text":"Which of the following is considered a first-line treatment for the treatment of acute asthma exacerbations?","explanation":"The **first-line** treatment for **acute asthma exacerbations** is inhaled **short-acting beta-agonists** (SABAs), such as albuterol. They act on beta-2 adrenergic receptors in the bronchial smooth muscle. As a result, bronchodilation occurs, quickly relieving bronchoconstriction associated with asthma exacerbations. The rapid onset of action is a notable advantage, providing immediate relief to the patient.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nInhaled long-acting beta-agonists are more suitable for long-term control when used in combination with inhaled corticosteroids.\r\n\r\nLeukotriene receptor antagonists are typically used as adjunct therapy for long-term control.\r\n\r\nOral antihistamines primarily target histamine receptors and are not effective for rapidly relieving bronchoconstriction during acute asthma exacerbations.\r\n\r\nInhaled corticosteroids are crucial for managing chronic inflammation in asthma and preventing exacerbations when used regularly. However, they are not the first-line treatment for providing immediate relief during acute exacerbations.","reference":"“Treatment of Acute Asthma Exacerbations - Pulmonary Disorders.” MSD Manual Professional Edition, https://www.msdmanuals.com/professional/pulmonary-disorders/asthma-and-related-disorders/treatment-of-acute-asthma-exacerbations. Accessed 21 Dec. 2023.","responses":[{"text":"Oral antihistamines","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inhaled long-acting beta-agonists","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inhaled short-acting beta-agonists","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Inhaled corticosteroids","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Leukotriene receptor antagonists","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21252,"text":"In addition to oxygen saturation, which of the following parameters should be closely monitored in a patient with acute asthma exacerbation to assess disease severity?","explanation":"**Peak expiratory flow rate** (PEFR) is a measure of how fast a person can exhale air during a forceful breath. Monitoring PEFR provides valuable information about the degree of airflow obstruction in the airways. A decrease in PEFR indicates worsening airflow limitation, making it a crucial parameter to assess the severity of asthma exacerbation.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nWhile fractional exhaled nitric oxide (FeNO) levels can be elevated in asthma, it is not routinely used to assess the severity of an acute exacerbation. It is more commonly used for assessing eosinophilic airway inflammation in stable asthma.\r\n\r\nTotal IgE levels are not specific to acute exacerbations and are not routinely monitored for assessing disease severity during an exacerbation.\r\n\r\nMonitoring serum pro-inflammatory cytokines is not a standard practice for assessing asthma exacerbation severity in clinical settings.\r\n\r\nWhile forced expiratory volume in one second (FEV1) is an important measure of lung function, PEFR is often preferred in acute settings due to its simplicity and ease of use.","reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 504.","responses":[{"text":"Total IgE","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Forced expiratory volume in one second (FEV1)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Serum pro-inflammatory cytokines","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fractional exhaled nitric oxide (FeNO)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Peak expiratory flow rate (PEFR)","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":21253,"text":"What is a common trigger for acute asthma exacerbation?","explanation":"**Asthma exacerbations** can be triggered by various factors, and respiratory infections, particularly **bacterial infections**, are known to be significant triggers. When the airways are infected with bacteria, it can lead to inflammation, increased mucus production, and bronchoconstriction, exacerbating asthma symptoms.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nWhile quitting smoking is beneficial for overall respiratory health, it is not a trigger for acute asthma exacerbation. In fact, smoking cessation is encouraged for individuals with asthma to improve lung function.\r\n\r\nWhile changes in weather, including high humidity, can trigger asthma symptoms in some individuals, it is not as consistently associated with acute exacerbations as bacterial infections.\r\n\r\nInhaled corticosteroids are a mainstay in the management of asthma and are not considered triggers for exacerbations. They help control inflammation in the airways and prevent acute episodes.\r\n\r\nEmotional stress can exacerbate asthma symptoms in some individuals, but bacterial infections are more commonly identified triggers for acute exacerbations.","reference":"Kumar, Vinay, et al. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed., Elsevier, 2020: 686.","responses":[{"text":"Bacterial infections","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Smoking cessation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"High humidity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inhaled corticosteroids","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Emotional stress","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21254,"text":"Pulmonary surfactant is essential for life as it lines the alveoli to lower surface\r\ntension, thereby preventing atelectasis during breathing. Surfactant is enriched\r\nwith a relatively unique phospholipid. What is this unique phospholipid termed as?","explanation":"**Dipalmitoylphosphatidylcholine** (DPPC) is a component of surfactant. It is a phospholipid that functions by reducing the surface tension at the air-liquid interface. As air moves in and out of the alveoli during breathing, the **surfactant** lowers the forces that tend to make the alveoli collapse.\r\n\r\nWithout sufficient surfactant, the surface tension in the alveoli would be higher, requiring greater effort to inflate the lungs during each breath and making them prone to collapse.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nCardiolipin is found in the inner mitochondrial membrane and it plays a role in maintaining the structural integrity of the mitochondrial membrane.\r\n\r\nMonopalmitoylphosphatidylethanolamine is found in cell membranes, but it is not a major component of pulmonary surfactant.\r\n\r\nCeramide is a key component of sphingolipids and is involved in cell signaling and regulation.\r\n\r\nTriacylglycerol is a neutral lipid involved in energy storage. Its main role is in lipid storage in adipose tissue.","reference":"Dipalmitoylphosphatidylcholine - an Overview | ScienceDirect Topics. https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/nursing-and-health-professions/dipalmitoylphosphatidylcholine#:~:text=Origin%20and%20Composition%20of%20Surfactant,(Figure%2046%2D7). Accessed 2 Dec. 2023.","responses":[{"text":"Cardiolipin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Triacylglycerol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ceramide","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dipalmitoylphosphatidylcholine","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Monopalmitoylphosphatdylethanolamine","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21255,"text":"If the partial pressure of (PCO2) increases in a patient due to airway obstruction, what will happen to the oxygen dissociation curve?","explanation":"An **increase in PCO2** (hypercapnia) and subsequent decrease in pH weaken the affinity of hemoglobin for oxygen. In an **acidic** environment, hemoglobin tends to release oxygen more readily to tissues, causing the oxygen dissociation curve to **shift to the right**. This shift is known as the Bohr effect.\r\n\r\nThis is particularly important in situations where tissues need more oxygen, such as during increased metabolic activity associated with airway obstruction.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nThe oxygen dissociation curve is influenced by factors like PCO2 and pH. An increase in PCO2 would cause a shift, so the curve would not remain the same.\r\n\r\nAn increase in PCO2 leads to a shift to the right, not the left.\r\n\r\nThe curve does not shift up or down in response to increased PCO2.","reference":"(1) Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 7th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2017: 32.\r\n(2) Oxygen Dissociation Curve - an Overview | ScienceDirect Topics. https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/nursing-and-health-professions/oxygen-dissociation-curve#:~:text=The%20oxygen%20dissociation%20curve%20is,partial%20pressures%20(Figure%205.1). Accessed 2 Dec. 2023.","responses":[{"text":"Shift down","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Remain the same","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Shift up","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Shift to left","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Shift to right","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":21257,"text":"Which of the following correctly represents the oxygen dissociation curve?","explanation":"The **oxygen dissociation curve** illustrates the relationship between the partial pressure of oxygen (PO2) and the saturation of hemoglobin with oxygen. The **sigmoidal** shape of the **curve** is crucial for understanding hemoglobin's cooperative binding of oxygen.\r\n\r\nAt lower PO2 values, hemoglobin has a lower affinity for oxygen, allowing it to easily release oxygen to tissues. As the PO2 increases, hemoglobin's affinity for oxygen increases, leading to efficient oxygen uptake in the lungs.","reference":"(1) Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 7th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2017: 29.\r\n(2) Gomez-Cambronero, Julian. “THE OXYGEN DISSOCIATION CURVE OF HEMOGLOBIN: BRIDGING THE GAP BETWEEN BIOCHEMISTRY AND PHYSIOLOGY.” Journal of Chemical Education, vol. 78, no. 6, June 2001, p. 757. PubMed Central, https://doi.org/10.1021/ed078p757.","responses":[{"text":"Linear","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sigmoidal","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Parabolic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Wavy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hyperbolic","correct":false,"visible":false}]}
]

